         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve"><head>Translation</head>
            <p>For the great god Hermes, Januarius, slave, as the votive offering which I offered for the safety and victory of Tiberius Claudius Jason Magnus, from my own means I laid the mosaics.</p></div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>The existence of this small shrine in close proximity to the so-called house of Jason Magnus, 
               like the colossal statue of Herakles which stood at the entrance to the atrium of the house, 
               should probably be connected with the ephebic cult of these two gods: see <ref type="inscription">C02300</ref>.  </p>
            <p></p>
            <p>For μέγας  as an epithet of Hermes, particularly in Egypt, see e.g OGIS 716 (Panopolis (= <bibl>
                  <title>PHI</title> 
                  <citedRange n="PH219130">219130</citedRange>
               </bibl>) and on the epithet in general Mueller, ΜΕΤΑΣ ΘΕΟΣ (Halle 1913, 322).  In the present context of gratitude to the god it might also be a reflection of an acclamation, cf. <bibl>Petersen <foreign xml:lang="grc">ΕΙΣ ΘΕΟΣ</foreign> 196f</bibl>; and it could also imply a connexion in the dedicator's mind with the <foreign xml:lang="grc">θεοὶ μεγάλοι</foreign> of Samothrace, cf. B. Hemberg, Die Kabiren (Uppsala, 1950) 26f. and 93f.</p>
            <p>Jason Magnus appears also in <ref type="inscription">C19400</ref> and <ref type="inscription">C19500</ref>, <ref type="inscription">C36100</ref>, 
               lines1, 2, and  <ref type="inscription">C25200</ref>, lines1, 2, the latter dated between 176 and 180, and probably in <ref type="inscription">C37700</ref>, 
               <ref type="inscription">C39700</ref>, line 2. 
               The prayer for his safety and victory may indicate that he was for a time a soldier, or possibly a competitor in some overseas contest.</p>
         </div>
         
